The "PML Initiation & Therapy Upsell" Workflow
Step 1: The Clinical Handoff (Post-Visit ). * After the initial assessment, the clinician messages the Admin team via Spruce: "Patient [Name] is approved for [X] weeks of PML. Initiate the Leave Track"
Step 2: The Admin Boundary & Therapy Audit.
Admin messages the patient to book Visit.
Script: "Dr. Al-Katib/Team has approved your medical leave. Your paperwork will be completed live during your next appointment. As a reminder, maintaining this leave requires active participation in our sleep, nutrition, and emotional intelligence/therapy. Please reply with your current therapist’s name, contact info, and appointment cadence so we can send a Release of Information (ROI) prior to your next visit."
Step 3: The Therapy Fork
If they have a therapist: Admin immediately sends the ROI to the external therapist to verify compliance.
If they DO NOT have a therapist: Admin executes the In-House Referral
Script: "Since you do not currently have a therapist, our protocol requires you to establish care to maintain your leave status. We highly recommend our in-house specialist, Celine, who works directly with our clinical team. Her rate is $250/session, and we offer Care Credit or internal payment plans to make this accessible. Shall I book your intake with her, or would you prefer our list of external insurance-based referrals?"
3. FRICTION POINTS & RISKS
The ROI Loophole: Patients will lie about seeing an outside therapist just to get you to sign their work forms. The Operational Fix: No PML forms are signed at Visit 2 unless the ROI from their external therapist is already returned and on file.
The Care Credit Friction: If the admin team is going to pitch Care Credit and payment plans for Celine, they need a 1-click link to send the patient. If the friction to apply for financing is too high, the patient will take the external referral list.
4. THE PML OBJECTION HANDLING MATRIX
(Instructions for Admin/Bianca: When a patient pushes back on the Executive Burnout Track requirements, DO NOT apologize and DO NOT negotiate. Copy, paste, and send the exact scripts below.)

Use when a patient pushes back on the frequency of visits, the cost of therapy, or the strictness of the timeline.)
"I completely understand that frequent visits and therapy feel like a lot right now when you are already exhausted. Our primary goal is your actual recovery. Dr. Al-Katib requires this protocol—regular visits, active therapy, and lifestyle tracking—because it is the clinical standard for getting you well.
Secondarily, we have to be honest about the insurance company: they demand continuous proof that you are actively recovering. If we don’t track these markers every 1-2 weeks, they will use that gap to deny the claim, and you will be left fighting them while trying to heal. We require this cadence to heal you first, and protect your paycheck second."


OBJECTION 1: The Financial Pushback
Patient says: "I can't afford $250 a session for Celine." or "Therapy is too expensive."
The Strategy: Anchor to their clinical recovery, validate the financial stress, and offer collaborative options.
The Script: > "I completely understand the financial stress. Because active therapy is a mandatory medical requirement to actually heal from this burnout and validate your Paid Medical Leave, we want to help you find a path that works. We have two options: 1) We can set you up with Care Credit today to finance your sessions with Celine, or 2) We can provide a list of external clinics that may take your insurance. Which option feels more manageable for you right now?"

OBJECTION 2: The Privacy / ROI Pushback
Patient says: "Why do you need to talk to my outside therapist ?" or "I don't want to sign an ROI."
The Strategy: Reassure them of their privacy while holding the line on coordination of care.
The Script: > "Because Dr. Al-Katib is legally signing off on your medical inability to work, our practice requires verified coordination of care to ensure you are getting the right support. We absolutely do not need your private therapy notes; we strictly need the ROI to confirm you are actively participating in the emotional recovery portion of your treatment plan. We cannot safely or legally authorize the medical leave without this verification on file."

OBJECTION 3: The "Just Sign It" Pushback
Patient says: "Can't Dr. Al-Katib just sign the form now and email it to me? I don't want to book another session just for paperwork."
The Strategy: Frame the live session as an act of thoroughness to prevent delays in their pay.
The Script: > "To ensure your employer or third-party receives 100% accurate information and your paycheck is not delayed, clinic policy mandates that all medical leave paperwork is completed live, together, during a clinical session. This ensures nothing is missed. As noted in the practice policy, form completion is charged at $200/hr without you around to answer the questions. Shall I book your follow-up for Tuesday or Thursday to get this completed together?"

OBJECTION 4: The Outright Refusal
Patient says: "I'm not doing therapy, and I'm not doing the lifestyle stuff. Just give me my meds and sign my form."
The Strategy: The polite, clinical ejection based on a mismatch of care philosophies.
The Script: > "Psychiatry in Motion is a holistic, active-recovery practice. Our ethical duty is to help you get better. Because you are declining the mandatory therapy and lifestyle protocols required to heal and maintain Paid Medical Leave under our care, we are unable to authorize your forms. We will gladly maintain your medication management for the next 30 days while you transition to a clinic that better fits your preferred treatment style, and I have attached a list of referrals."



